snippet.textDisplay: I think that’s the problem with this, is everyone has a different idea of what an introvert/extrovert is. An extrovert to me would be, not necessarily loud, but someone who loves being around others and thrives in that atmosphere whereas an introvert would be someone who thrives on their own. Not necessarily loud/quiet. This video focuses too much on the loud/quiet when in reality a lot of extroverts can be quiet and chill and vice versa. But like I said everyone’s idea on what they are is different

That isn't a good thing, it means you lack essential qualities for lots of jobs, such as communication and social skills. For example, you couldn't be a CEO, a manager, a doctor, a lawyer, a pilot, a surgeon, a nurse, a receptionist, a supervisor, in fact, rule out anything to do with medicine altogether! Now before anyone says "Oh that's not true!" or "That's not fair!" Let me tell you that in fact ALL of those jobs require communication skills! If you don't have those... well then.

snippet.textDisplay:
to be honest as an introvert, people keep describing themselves as introverts when they're not, because its just a "trend" nowadays.
being an introvert doesnt mean that if you dont go out you're an introvert, if you're quiet and shy you're an introvert.
it means being uncomfortable in big, loud places, not fitting in those big crowds and just liking being at home, as an introvert, i AM very awkward but i can handle a convorsation better than most extroverts do, i just dont feel comfortable going into parties and stuff.
